==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|yi|en}}, from {{etyl|he|en}} {{term|קיבוץ||a gathering|lang=he|tr=kibúts}}. Alternatively, from colloquial {{etyl|de|en}} {{term|kiebitzen||to be an onlooker at a game|lang=de}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A person who offers unsolicited views, advice, or criticism; one who [[kibitz]]es.
#: ''Did I ask you what you thought about my card hand, you [[kibitzer]]!''
#* '''1971''', {{w|John Updike}}, ''New York Times'' review on '{{w|Rabbit Redux}}', 05/11/71, [http://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/05/books/updike-rabbit.html],
#*: Neither good nor evil exactly, he is the ultimate catalyst or '''kibitzer''', a blue-note howl of pain and laughter such as Charlie Parker might have blown.

